</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="661" pageId="15" pageNumber="660" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,220,1587]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1127,218,369]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="661" pageId="15" pageNumber="660">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,352,1564,1587]" pageId="15" pageNumber="660">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The species is characterized by elytral setae on apical declivity semierect to erect, rostrum in males enlarged apicad, with epistome wider than epifrons. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Borovec &amp; Skuhrovec, 2017" authorityName="Borovec &amp; Skuhrovec" authorityYear="2017" box="[179,275,250,273]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Epistomius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janaki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[179,275,250,273]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="661">E. janaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[282,366,250,273]" pageId="16" pageNumber="661" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, from which it can be distinguished by the following characters: elytral setae on posterior declivity long and slender, pointed, twice as long as conspicuous setae on basal half; tarsomere II 1.3–1.4× as wide as long; elytra in males longer, 1.15–1.18× as long as wide; and penis short, about as long as wide, at apex obtuse, tip not separated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
